        <h1>How to Choose a Tuition Centre in Singapore: A Parent&rsquo;s Guide</h1>
        <div class="blog-post-meta">
          <a class="blog-author" href="/about/" rel="author">By Jeremy Lim, Founder</a>
          <span>&middot;</span>
          <time datetime="2026-05-27">27 May 2026</time>
          <span>&middot;</span>
          <span class="blog-reading-time">7 min read</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="blog-post-body">
        <p>Singapore has thousands of tuition centres, and almost all of them say the same things: experienced tutors, proven results, small classes. For a parent, the hard part isn&rsquo;t finding options &mdash; it&rsquo;s telling them apart. Choosing well matters far more than choosing quickly: the right fit can lift a grade and rebuild confidence, while the wrong one wastes months you don&rsquo;t have before the O- or A-Levels. Here are the seven things that actually distinguish a good centre from an expensive one &mdash; and the red flags worth walking away from.</p>

        <h2>1. Class size &mdash; and whether it&rsquo;s real</h2>
        <p>&ldquo;Small classes&rdquo; means nothing without a number. A class of 6 and a class of 20 are completely different experiences: in a small group your child gets their work seen and corrected every session; in a large one they can sit unnoticed for weeks. Ask for the <em>maximum</em> class size, not the average, and ask how often the tutor reviews each student&rsquo;s written work. If the answer is vague, assume the classes are bigger than implied.</p>

        <h2>2. A method, not just more worksheets</h2>
        <p>Most centres&rsquo; core offering is volume: more practice papers, more drilling. But a child who keeps making the same mistakes doesn&rsquo;t need more reps of the wrong technique &mdash; they need a <em>method</em>. Ask how the centre teaches a student to approach a question they&rsquo;ve never seen before. A good answer describes a repeatable thinking process; a weak one just promises &ldquo;lots of practice.&rdquo; The difference shows up most when the exam question doesn&rsquo;t match anything in the practice stack.</p>

        <h2>3. Who actually teaches your child</h2>
        <p>Find out who stands in front of the class &mdash; the named, experienced tutor you saw in the marketing, or a rotating cast of part-timers? Continuity matters: a tutor who knows your child&rsquo;s specific weaknesses across the term will move them faster than four different relief tutors ever will. Ask about the tutor&rsquo;s background and whether the same person teaches every week.</p>

        <h2>4. Proof, not just claims</h2>
        <p>Every centre advertises results. The credible ones can show you <em>specific</em> transformations &mdash; a student who moved from C5 to A2 and how &mdash; not just a wall of distinction percentages with no context. Be sceptical of figures with no story behind them, and ask to see or hear about students whose starting point resembled your child&rsquo;s.</p>

        <h2>5. Transparent, all-inclusive fees</h2>
        <p>Hidden costs are common: registration fees, material fees, deposit, and long lock-in contracts that make leaving expensive. A centre confident in its teaching will publish its fees, keep them month-to-month, and include materials. If you have to email to get a price, or you&rsquo;re asked to commit to a year upfront, treat both as warning signs.</p>

        <h2>6. A real way to try before you commit</h2>
        <p>You shouldn&rsquo;t have to gamble months of fees to find out whether a centre fits. A free diagnostic assessment or a trial lesson lets you see the teaching, and lets the centre show (rather than tell) what they&rsquo;d do for your child. A centre that won&rsquo;t let you sample anything before paying is asking for a lot of trust it hasn&rsquo;t earned yet.</p>

        <h2>7. Fit with your child</h2>
        <p>Finally, the intangible: does your child come out of a session clearer and a little more confident, or just more tired? The best centre on paper is the wrong one if your child dreads going. Pay attention to how they feel after the first few lessons &mdash; it&rsquo;s the most honest data you&rsquo;ll get.</p>

        <h2>Red flags to walk away from</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Guaranteed grades.</strong> No honest tutor can promise an A &mdash; learning doesn&rsquo;t work that way.</li>
          <li><strong>Pressure to sign a long contract</strong> before your child has attended a single lesson.</li>
          <li><strong>Vague answers</strong> about class size, who teaches, or what the actual fee is.</li>
          <li><strong>&ldquo;Just do more practice&rdquo;</strong> as the entire strategy, with no method behind it.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>A simple way to decide</h2>
        <p>Shortlist two or three centres, ask the questions above, and book a free assessment at each. Within a couple of sessions you&rsquo;ll know which one your child responds to. That&rsquo;s the whole decision &mdash; not the glossiest brochure, but the place where your child actually starts to improve.</p>
        <p>At A-Worthy we built around exactly these criteria: a maximum of six per class, the SHARP Method rather than endless worksheets, the same tutor every week, transparent month-to-month fees, and a free assessment so you can judge the teaching before you commit a cent.</p>
